1.2 Overview of Methodology¶

The first step in our modelling technique is to transform the entire dataset that was already cleansed in Phase I. We changed the data after pre-processing in Phase 1 by encoding categorical descriptive features as numerical and then scaled the descriptive characteristics. Following that, we divided the data into training and test sets in a 70:30 ratio. To be explicit, the 2145 rows of data used during the hyperparameter tuning phase are referred to as the training data. The test data is the 920 rows of data utilised during the performance comparison phase.

We use the sophisticated Random Forest Importance approach inside a pipeline to select the best features before fitting a particular classifier on the training data. After encoding category features, we consider 10, 20, and the entire set of features (with 31 features). We undertake 5-fold stratified cross-validation to fine-tune hyperparameters of each classifier using the area under the curve (AUC) as the performance metric, using feature selection and hyperparameter search within a single pipeline. We use parallel processing with "-2" cores to create each model.

Because the target feature has a higher number of rent prices below $1500 per month (an unbalanced target class issue), stratification is necessary to ensure that each validation set has the same number of classes as the original dataset. During the search, we additionally look at the sensitivity of each model to its hyperparameters. We "fit" the tuned classifiers on the test data using 10-fold cross-validation in a paired fashion after identifying the three tuned classifiers (with the optimal hyperparameter values), and we do paired t-tests to evaluate if any performance difference is statistically significant. We also compare the classifiers on the test data in terms of their recall scores and confusion matrices.

We consider the following (binary) classifiers to predict the target feature:
K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN),
Decision trees (DT), and
Naive Bayes (NB).

3.2.1. K-Nearest Neighbors(KNN) ¶

Here, we will use Pipeline to stack feature selection and grid search for KNN hyperparameter tuning via cross-validation. We will use the same Pipeline methodology for NB and DT. The KNN hyperparameters are as follows:

  • number of neighbors (n_neighbors) and
  • the distance metric p

For feature selection, we use the powerful Random Forest Importance (RFI) method with 100 estimators. To make RFI feature selection as part of the pipeline, we have performed below step. For this reason, we define the custom RFIFeatureSelector() class below to pass in RFI as a step to the pipeline

We have imported BaseEstimator and TransformerMixin to perform the steps.

In [17]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin
class RFIFeatureSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    
    def __init__(self, n_features_=10):
        self.n_features_ = n_features_
        self.fs_indices_ = None

# Now, we will over ride the fit function and then the Transform function as well.

   # override the fit function
    def fit(self, X, y):
        from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
        from numpy import argsort
        model_rfi = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100)
        model_rfi.fit(X, y)
        self.fs_indices_ = argsort(model_rfi.feature_importances_)[::-1][0:self.n_features_] 
        return self 
    
    # override the transform function
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        return X[:, self.fs_indices_]
In [18]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

pipe_KNN = Pipeline(steps=[('rfi_fs', RFIFeatureSelector()), 
                           ('knn', KNeighborsClassifier())])

params_pipe_KNN = {'rfi_fs__n_features_': [10, 20, Data.shape[1]],
                   'knn__n_neighbors': [1, 5, 10, 15, 20],
                   'knn__p': [1, 2]}

gs_pipe_KNN = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipe_KNN, 
                           param_grid=params_pipe_KNN, 
                           cv=cv_method,
                           refit=True,
                           n_jobs=-2,
                           scoring='roc_auc',
                           verbose=1)

In [22]:
def get_search_results(gs):

    def model_result(scores, params):
        scores = {'mean_score': np.mean(scores),
             'std_score': np.std(scores),
             'min_score': np.min(scores),
             'max_score': np.max(scores)}
        return pd.Series({**params,**scores})

    models = []
    scores = []

    for i in range(gs.n_splits_):
        key = f"split{i}_test_score"
        r = gs.cv_results_[key]        
        scores.append(r.reshape(-1,1))

    all_scores = np.hstack(scores)
    for p, s in zip(gs.cv_results_['params'], all_scores):
        models.append((model_result(s, p)))

    pipe_results = pd.concat(models, axis=1).T.sort_values(['mean_score'], ascending=False)

    columns_first = ['mean_score', 'std_score', 'max_score', 'min_score']
    columns = columns_first + [c for c in pipe_results.columns if c not in columns_first]

    return pipe_results[columns]

3.2.2 (Gaussian) Naive Bayes (NB)¶

The next algorithm we fit on our dataset is Gaussian Naive Bayes model. As we don't have much information about our dataset, we will be using var_smoothing. By default, the var_smoothing parameter's value is $10-^9$ . We conduct the grid search in the logspace (over the powers of 10) sourced from NumPy. We start with 10 and end with $10^3$' with 200 different values, but we perform a random search over only 20 different values (for shorter run times). Since NB requires each descriptive feature to follow a Gaussian distribution, we first perform a power transformation on the input data before model fitting.

In [25]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PowerTransformer
D_train_transformed = PowerTransformer().fit_transform(D_train)

from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

pipe_NB = Pipeline([('rfi_fs', RFIFeatureSelector()), 
                     ('nb', GaussianNB())])

params_pipe_NB = {'rfi_fs__n_features_': [10, 20, Data.shape[1]],
                  'nb__var_smoothing': np.logspace(1,-3, num=200)}

n_iter_search = 20
gs_pipe_NB = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=pipe_NB, 
                          param_distributions=params_pipe_NB, 
                          cv=cv_method,
                          refit=True,
                          n_jobs=-2,
                          scoring='roc_auc',
                          n_iter=n_iter_search,
                          verbose=1) 

gs_pipe_NB.fit(D_train_transformed, t_train);

3.3 Model Comparison ¶

In the above steps of hyperparameter tuning phase, we used 2145 rows in our training data within a cross-validation framework and with the help of that we found out the best hyperparameter values for each of the three classifiers. Now we will try to fit each tuned classifier on the remaining 920 rows in the test data in a cross-validated fashion to figure out which (tuned) classifier performs the best. We will also like to perform pair T-test to find out the difference between the performance of two classifiers and if there is any difference whether it is statistically significant or not.

Following are steps we will going to follow:

  1. We will perform 10-fold stratified cross-validation on every classifier.
  2. We will conduct a paired t-test for the AUC score between the following (tuned) classifier combinations:
    KNN vs. NB,
    KNN vs. DT,
    DT vs. NB.

We will use 10-fold stratified cross-validation evaluation method for hyperparameter tuning and name it as cv_method_test and going to use in every step.We are using the fix random state in every step during the cross-validation, it means that all the classifiers were fitted and tested on the same partitions and making our results paired in statiscal sense.

In [39]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

cv_method_test = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, random_state=111)
In [40]:

                                 X=D_test,
                                 y=t_test,

                                 scoring='roc_auc')

Out[42]:
0.754

In the above step, we have same random state which makes the classifier paired. So, we will now use stats.ttest_rel function to run the following (paired) t-tests.

The value of paired t-test can be measured in two ways:

  1. P- value is lower 0.05, which means that the difference is statistically significant.
  2. P- value is higher 0.05, which means that the difference is not statistically significant.

Now, lets run the test and find out the difference is statistically significant or not.

In [43]:
from scipy import stats

print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_KNN, cv_results_NB))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_DT, cv_results_KNN))
print(stats.ttest_rel(cv_results_DT, cv_results_NB))

Ttest_relResult(statistic=1.1847216030736727, pvalue=0.26646822475509674)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-2.9717824938264514, pvalue=0.015657047014539845)
Ttest_relResult(statistic=-1.09976889401075, pvalue=0.2999782281140095)

We observe that the p-value of our paired t-test higher than 0.05. Thus, we conclude that, at a 95% significance level, even though the accuracy of best KNN model is slightly higher compared to that of DT and NB, this difference is not statistically significant.

4. Critique and Limitations¶

There are a few problems and limits in our modelling technique. To begin, we used a black-box method since we valued raw prediction performance over interpretability. In the future, we might think about doing a more in-depth examination of the feature selection and ranking process, as well as our hyperparameter space choices. Second, when creating the NB, we used a blanket power transformation on the training data, ignoring the dummy features in the dataset. This could explain why the NB performed so poorly on the test set. Building a Gaussian NB and a Bernoulli NB separately on numerical and dummy descriptive features is one such solution. Because NB assumes inter-independence conditioned on the value of the target feature, we may get a final prediction by multiplying predictions from each model. Third, for both training and testing, we only used a tiny fraction of the entire dataset to reduce run times. Because data is always valuable, we could re-run our experiments using all of the data while ensuring that the train and test splits are done correctly. The KNN classifier outperforms the other two models statistically. As a result, we may be able to improve it by widening the hyperparameter search space and integrating other classification technique parameters. Furthermore, random forests and other ensemble approaches based on trees can be considered as possibly better models.

5. Summary & Conclusions¶

The following section compromises of three sub-sections, they are listed below.

5.1 Project Summary¶

The report is based on the predicting the rent price of apartments on the basis of various factors such as housing type, sqfeet, number of beds,pets allowed etc. We have prepared this report in 2 Phases: Phase 1 and Phase 2.

In Phase 1, I imported the data and provided a descriptive summary of the features available in dataset, and then perform data pre-processing by importing the dataset. After importing we saw the shape of dataset which shows that dataset has 265190 rows and 22 columns. After that, i took a subset of dataset containing 5000 rows only and then we see the datatypes of the variables. After that i remove the missing values present in the dataset as they can cause some issues in future. Once the missing values are removed we can see that there 3065 rows and 22 columns present in the dataset. After that i renamed the columns. Then we see the summary of all variables of dataset and the unique values present in the categorical columns. Then we begin the visualizations and showed the visualization which exhibits the relationship between our target feature and various other variables included in our dataset.That's all we have done in this report/Phase 1

In Phase 2, I first imported the pre-processed dataset in Phase 1. After importing the dataset, we performed one hot encoding on our dataset. Our target feature Rent Price has various numeric observations, which could create problem in further steps of the report. So, we replaced the values our target feature into 0 and 1. 0 represented all the prices below 1500 pm and 1 represented all the prices above 1500 pm. After that, we Scaled our unscaled dataset. After Scaling the dataset, we splitted the dataset into ratio of 70:30 for training and testing for performing the various algorithms on them. The training section has 2145 rows while test section has 920 rows. After that, we Selected the best 10 feature present in our dataset by using Random Forest Importance(RFI) and visualize them on a plot. Then we fit our training dataset on three different classifiers and tuned them:

  • K-Nearest Neighbors(KNN)

  • (Gaussian) Naive Bayes (NB)

  • Decision Trees (DT)

For each classifier, we find the best parameter, best score and also checked if any other better combination is available or not and then visualize them.

The last we performed is the comparison between these three classifier.In this step,I have fitted the three classifier on the test dataset. We have compared all the three algorithms by using cross validation feature and perform paired T-test on them and observed their P-values and commented on it. The best performing algorithm was KNN.

5.2 Summary of Findings¶

On the training data, the K-nearest Neighbors(KNN) model delivers the maximum cross-validated AUC score with 10 of the best features picked using Random Forest Importance (RFI). Furthermore, when tested on test data (in a cross-validated manner), the K-nearest Neighbors(KNN) model again surpasses both Naive Bayes and Decision Tree models in terms of AUC.The Naive Bayes model, on the other hand, has the highest recall score on the test data. When conditioned on the values of the hyperparameters in general, we also notice that our models are not highly sensitive to the amount of features selected by RFI. As a result, it appears that working with ten features rather than the entire feature set is preferable, as this may prevent overfitting and result in models that are easier to train and understand.

5.3 Conclusions¶

The main of our Project report was to predict the monthly rental prices of apartments based on various variables available. In this report, we fitted various algorithms on the dataset to evaluate our aim. We found out that the KNN model is the best algorithm that predicts our target feature:- Rent Price. After fitting the tuned classifier on the remaining test model, we found that KNN is still the best Performing Model. So, we can say that KNN is the best model in our dataset, when it comes to predicting the target feature.
